Humans comprise about 100 million tonnes of the Earth's dry biomass,&lt;ref&gt;The world [[human population]] was 6.6 billion in January 2008. At an average weight of 100 pounds (30 lbs of biomass), that equals 100 million tonnes.{{clarify| For this value, more than 7bn people are needed in my calculation. And the wet biomass &quot;420Mt&quot; claim doesn't fit to this either|date=April 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[domesticate]]d animals about 700 million tonnes, [[earthworms]] over 1,100 million tonnes,&lt;ref name=Blakemore2017 /&gt; and annual cereal [[agriculture|crops]] about 2.3 billion tonnes.&lt;ref&gt;FAO Statistical Yearbook 2013: page 130 - http://www.fao.org/docrep/018/i3107e/i3107e.PDF&lt;/ref&gt;

The most successful [[animal]] species, in terms of biomass, may well be [[Antarctic krill]], ''Euphausia superba'', with a fresh biomass approaching 500 million [[tonne]]s,&lt;ref name=&quot;KrillBiomass2009&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.dsr.2008.12.007 | vauthors = Atkinson A, Siegel V, Pakhomov EA, Jessopp MJ, Loeb V | year = 2009 | title = A re-appraisal of the total biomass and annual production of Antarctic krill | journal = Deep-Sea Research Part I | volume = 56 | pages = 727–740 | url = http://www.iced.ac.uk/documents/Atkinson%20et%20al,%20Deep%20Sea%20Research%20I,%202009.pdf | issue = 5 | bibcode = 2009DSRI...56..727A }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;NE97&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Ross, R. M. and Quetin, L. B. (1988). Euphausia superba: a critical review of annual production. Comp. Biochem. Physiol. 90B, 499-505.&lt;/ref&gt; although domestic cattle may also reach these immense figures.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}} However, as a group, the small aquatic [[crustacean]]s called [[copepod]]s may form the largest animal biomass on earth.&lt;ref name=Ossietzky&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html|title=Biology of Copepods |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101205840/http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html |archive-date=1 January 2009 |publisher=[[Carl von Ossietzky University of Oldenburg]]|website=uni-oldenburg.de}}&lt;/ref&gt; A 2009 paper in ''Science'' estimates, for the first time, the total world fish biomass as somewhere between 0.8 and 2.0 billion tonnes.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilson RW, Millero FJ, Taylor JR, Walsh PJ, Christensen V, Jennings S, Grosell M | s2cid = 36321414 | title = Contribution of fish to the marine inorganic carbon cycle | journal = Science | volume = 323 | issue = 5912 | pages = 359–362 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19150840 | doi = 10.1126/science.1157972 | bibcode = 2009Sci...323..359W }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.physorg.com/news151251277.html Researcher gives first-ever estimate of worldwide fish biomass and impact on climate change] ''[[PhysOrg.com]]'', 15 January 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; It has been estimated that about 1% of the global biomass is due to [[phytoplankton]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | vauthors = Bidle KD, Falkowski PG | title = Cell death in planktonic, photosynthetic microorganisms | journal = Nature Reviews. Microbiology | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 643–655 | date = August 2004 | pmid = 15263899 | doi = 10.1038/nrmicro956 | s2cid = 15741047 }}&lt;/ref&gt; and 25% is due to [[fungi]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | last1 = Miller | first1 = JD | year = 1992 | title = Fungi as contaminants in indoor air | journal = Atmospheric Environment | volume = 26 | issue = 12| pages = 2163–2172 | doi=10.1016/0960-1686(92)90404-9|bibcode = 1992AtmEn..26.2163M }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | vauthors = Sorenson WG | title = Fungal spores: hazardous to health? | journal = Environmental Health Perspectives | volume = 107 Suppl 3 | issue = Suppl 3 | pages = 469–472 | date = June 1999 | pmid = 10423389 | pmc = 1566211 | doi = 10.1289/ehp.99107s3469 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

